@@yRoc Road@@N

  Not merely a road between places. Roc Road is a @@enegotiated artery@@N
between two civilizations: @@yMidgaard@@N, whose authority rests on stone
law and institutional continuity, and @@yKiess@@N, whose survival depends
on adaptive commerce and hard-edged logistical pragmatism. The road
persists because neither model can survive in isolation.

  Its modern form overlays at least four historical strata: a pre-city
migration track following ridges and stable fords, a formalized stone
route under old-kingdom road canon, a war-era military supply corridor,
and a post-war mercantile reconstruction spine. Every major segment
carries visible traces of prior regimes.

  Midgaard's imprint appears in the eastern half: @@Wash-mortar paving@@N,
drainage cuts graded to prevent washout, and milestone fragments
bearing the Three Civic Oaths. Road wardens recite these oaths at
every shift change and repaint boundary sigils even when manpower
shortages prevent full repairs, because the Oath of Stone requires
visible evidence of maintained jurisdiction.

  Kiess controls the western half through @@yconvoy compacts@@N -- contracts
binding caravan operators, guards, and waystation custodians into
shared liability pools. A Kiess convoy marshal manages actual traffic
flow, delaying departures during threat spikes and authorizing
emergency reroutes through the Greenveil Spur.

  The @@eCrossroads@@N at the corridor's center is the political heart,
where Midgaard charter boundaries blur and Kiess convoy insurance
clauses begin to dominate. Violence spikes whenever one side attempts
unilateral control. Shared governance reduces bloodshed but increases
corruption.

  Along the route stands the @@lViolet Eclipse Cathedral@@N, a threshold
institution where arcane containment doctrine meets road-traffic
reality. Waystations, banner posts, and bridge works dot the corridor,
each maintained by whichever jurisdiction can afford to keep it
standing.

  The road was built on the ruins of fallen @@dEvermeet@@N. When that
western city collapsed, Roc Road became a corridor of displacement
rather than commerce. Kiess rose on Evermeet's foundations with a
founding charter that explicitly repudiated predecessor-era sealed
warrants -- making the western terminus a legal refutation of abuses
committed along the eastern half.

  Where Midgaard asks @@W"Who has lawful right to command?"@@N Kiess asks
@@y"What keeps goods and people alive to arrive tomorrow?"@@N Roc Road's
identity is built from that unresolved argument.
